0.2.6

- A mirror repository was created on GitLab; it will be synchronized regularly with the GitHub repository. However, GitHub will remain the primary repository, so they may—at times—be out of sync for up to several weeks.

- The file "history.txt" was renamed to "CHANGELOG" to align with the naming convention used on GitLab.

0.2.5

- ShellDOS can now run on read-only devices by loading the default configuration; if the device allows writing, it checks for the existence of a configuration file—creating a default one if none is found—but reverts to the base configuration if writing fails.

- ShellDOS now applies the default configuration loaded from the configuration file; however, this implementation is still in the early stages, affecting only the header colors (partially) and the option to show or hide the header. There are still some bugs that will be addressed in future versions.

0.2.4

- The code was reorganized by moving files into different folders to improve organization and make it easier to understand and maintain. Some duplicate headers were found, so the code was cleaned up a bit.

0.2.3

- The "ver" command now also displays the bit-depth for which the console is available; additionally, the message "Type HELP or press F1 = Help" now appears at the top, indicating that help can be accessed by pressing the F1 key or typing the command into the console.

- Only the headers for calling standard MS-DOS internal commands have been set up; headers for handling PATH, other "sensitive" functions, or memory management are not yet in place—these might only be available for 16-bit mode.

0.2.2


- Several buffer types of varying sizes were defined to avoid always using the same ones and to save memory by not relying on a single, fixed buffer size. However, the size was increased to accommodate potentially long user commands, without making them absurdly large.

- The current path is now a global variable, just like the configuration file path; the latter remains unchanged and is automatically assigned upon launching shdos.exe.

- Fixed an issue where the executable's current path was being overwritten by the configuration file path; the two variables have now been separated.

- shDOS now displays a prompt similar to DOS systems (e.g., C:\DOS>), but shows the actual path from which the program is running.

- Implemented a "trim" function to improve command validation by removing leading and trailing whitespace from the captured input.

- Implemented shellpath variable; while currentpath holds the current working directory (which changes with the cd command), shellpath remains constant—much like confpath, which stores the fixed path to the configuration file.

- Partially implemented external command execution; it's now possible to "execute" certain external commands. The process isolates the executable name and checks for .exe, .bat, or (for 16-bit) .com formats. If the check passes, it confirms the executable exists; if the command lacks an extension, it checks the current directory for corresponding .exe, .bat, or .com variants. If all checks fail, it indicates the command is invalid. Currently, commands must be located in the same folder as shdos.exe.

0.2.1

- Implementation of the CONFIGURATION structure, which serves as a template for creating the "shdos.cfg" file that stores the default ShellDOS configuration.

- Was discovered that the system was crashing in DOSBox due to excessive memory consumption. With the applied changes, it now works without problems.

- ShellDOS detects if the shdos.cfg file exists. If it exists, loads the configuration (although it's not yet applied); otherwise, it creates the file with default values. Successfully tested on Dosbox, FreeDOS, MS-DOS, Windows 95, 7, and 11. It works well in ReactOS, but the 16-bit version runs very slowly when typing a command; the 32-bit version works perfectly.

- Although the system works, I found that if it's run from a CD-ROM, the system crashes because don't validate that the media is read-only. The .exe file needs to be copied to a different location; I'll fix that problem.

0.2.0

- Use the buffer size defined by the constant MAX_BUFFER for array sizes, protecting the size of the entered command by adhering to the MAX_BUFFER buffer size.

- The snprintf function was used before using print_colored_text, but if the text size to be used was larger than the buffer size, the program would cause an overflow upon closing. Now, snprintf, which uses the buffer size, is used, and this problem no longer occurs.

- First partial implementation of the "commands" module, where the code for internal commands common to both 16-bit and 32-bit systems will be placed. Otherwise, they will only be declared in commands.h, but each version (16-bit and 32-bit) will have its own implementation. Otherwise, they will remain in commands.c. Organize the source code too.


0.1.2

- Text coloring functions were successfully implemented, and the console header function was prepared to mimic the style of the Reactos console (discontinued in recent versions). Currently, this only works on 16-bit systems.

- Text coloring was implemented for 32-bit systems. The console text was also forced to be white, as it was appearing green when run on the Windows 11 console. This will be configurable later.

- The ver and cls commands were implemented, returning the current ShellDOS version and clearing the screen, respectively.

- The base commands were set to display in light gray. This works on 16-bit versions, but when run on Windows 11, the base color is light green, and the title is also light blue. Microsoft changed this to modernize its color palette in the Windows 11 command prompt (use color themes in cmd configuration) (I'm not sure if this happens in Windows 10). This will need to be adjusted in later versions.

0.1.1

- Part of the code was rewritten to support the getCmdWidth function, making it available for both 16-bit and 32-bit systems. Now, each project has its own main.c file containing the necessary libraries, but each will load a 16bits.c or 32bits.c file when operating system-specific functions are required.

- The getCmdWidth function was successfully tested on FreeDOS, MS-DOS, and Windows 95. It worked correctly for the 16-bit executable, returning 80 columns. When tested on Windows 11 (command console), the same function returned 83 columns from the 32-bit executable.

0.1.0

- ShDOS project started, a repository was created on Github, the goal is to create a cmd for 16-32 bits running from the command console but that will bring more commands and features than the current Windows console.

- The basic structure of the program was started with the necessary files and folders.

- I started implementing reading from the keyboard, it is already saved in an array "command" and it checks what the user typed. There are still problems with special keys like uppercase which was resolved, but there could be issues with others.

- The code was improved a bit, now it works well when pressing the shift key (it no longer introduces a blank space when pressed), the code was moved to C instead of C++ since classes will not be used and the size of the final .exe has been reduced. The boot code was moved to core.h/.c to be reusable in both 16-bit and 32-bit mode at the same time.